    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The Principle of Least Privilege (PoLP) is the most important rule in the world of security, and it is a rule that is strictly enforced by the most important people in the world: the **golems** and the **goblins**.\n\nImagine a **goblin** who has been given a key to the entire castle. That key is the password to the entire castle. But the **goblin** is also a **goblin**, and the **goblin** has a very specific set of rules: \"I can only open doors that are marked 'Goblin Access'.\" If the **goblin** tries to open a door marked \"Human Access,\" they will be **goblin**-ed out immediately.\n\nIn the real world, this means a user account should only have the permissions necessary to do exactly one thing. If a user account is used to manage the network, it should not have the ability to read the user's own password, or it should not have the ability to change the network configuration.\n\n### Real-World Examples\n\n**1. The \"Goblin\" in the Network**\nImagine a **goblin** who has been given a key to the entire castle. That key is the",
