    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The Principle of Least Privilege (PoLP) is a fundamental security concept that dictates a user or system account should be granted only the minimum level of access necessary to perform its specific functions. In a corporate network, this means a developer account should not have the ability to read customer data, while a network administrator account should not have the ability to modify firewall rules or access sensitive financial databases.\n\nTechnically, this is implemented by assigning the most granular permissions possible to each user or service account. For example, a standard user account might be granted read-only access to the file system, whereas a service account running a backup utility might be granted read-write access only to the specific directory containing the backup files. This ensures that if a user account is compromised, the attacker is limited to the specific resources they were authorized to access, significantly reducing the potential damage and the complexity of the attack.",
      "source": "target",
